  <h2 id="accessibility">Accessibility Checks (WCAG Compliance)</h2>

  <p>
    Accessibility isn't just good practice—it's increasingly important for SEO and may be legally required. Crawlix performs 10+ WCAG-aligned checks:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Images without alt text</strong> (WCAG 1.1.1) - Non-decorative images need descriptions</li>
    <li><strong>Form inputs without labels</strong> (WCAG 1.3.1, 4.1.2) - Every input needs an associated label</li>
    <li><strong>Buttons without accessible names</strong> (WCAG 4.1.2) - Buttons need text or aria-label</li>
    <li><strong>Links without accessible names</strong> (WCAG 2.4.4) - Links need descriptive text</li>
    <li><strong>Missing language attribute</strong> (WCAG 3.1.1) - <code>lang</code> required on HTML element</li>
    <li><strong>Missing skip-to-content link</strong> (WCAG 2.4.1) - Helps keyboard navigation</li>
    <li><strong>Duplicate IDs</strong> (WCAG 4.1.1) - IDs must be unique</li>
    <li><strong>Positive tabindex</strong> - Disrupts natural tab order</li>
    <li><strong>Auto-playing media</strong> (WCAG 1.4.2) - Audio/video shouldn't autoplay</li>
    <li><strong>Tables without headers</strong> - Data tables need <code>&lt;th&gt;</code> elements</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="international-seo">International SEO Checks</h2>

  <p>For multilingual and multi-regional sites:</p>

  <ul>
